// ch05 §5.12: "Capturing more than one name by reference (`[&a, &b]`)
// ties the closure's own lifetime to all of them jointly -- the same
// conservative default-grouping treatment §5.3 already gives a function
// with several ungrouped reference parameters." `f`'s body only reads
// `a`, but `b` is also captured by reference -- writing to `b` (never
// even used inside the closure body) while `f` is still alive must still
// be rejected, proving the closure's live borrow jointly covers every
// by-reference capture, not just the ones the body happens to use.
int main() {
    int a = 1;
    int b = 2;
    auto f = [&a, &b]() { return a; };
    b = 100;
    return f();
}
